I often wonder if millennials might be the last generation able to appreciate art purely and connect with artists without the pressure to view everything critically.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when there was a shared understanding of pop culture, and that collective consciousness has vanished now.
In those days, we could immerse ourselves directly in the content without having to consider its origins, because tracing it back then wasn't easy.
We worshipped these artists as gods, and there was no reason to question this adoration. As a result, we established a kind of "quasi-social relationship" with them, which became an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so enamored with nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch it together while eating pizza.
This contrasts with the experience we have now with streaming platforms, which typically release 12 episodes at once, allowing everyone to watch at their own pace, and where people post about the plot with "spoiler warnings" or only discuss in specific groups.
In the subconscious, we all yearn for the sense of collective belonging that ties us all together.
It's precisely this nostalgia that makes us revisit shows like "The Office" or movies like "Pride & Prejudice," with their iconic lines circulating widely online like memes, which we can quote to each other and assume most people will understand.
We quote these iconic lines from the shows and assume that most people will get the reference.
Now, even if something goes viral online, we can't assume that everyone has seen it.
With information exploding, there's so much we need to pay attention to that we can hardly simplify it… Do we have a chance to escape this state of information overload?
We discover new media and new artists again and again, only to find they are either notorious abusers or stubborn bigots, a cycle that is tiresome.
We indulge in nostalgia while acknowledging that the creators of the art we love may have serious moral flaws, a contradiction that leaves us at a loss.
We will be more cautious in building a "quasi-social relationship" with artists.
We gradually realize that if someone wants to gain wealth and power, they will find it hard not to hurt others or exploit them.
Since the collective consciousness of the media no longer exists, we have formed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Naturally, some still refuse to see this and try to elevate others to god-like status, only to look shocked when their idols fall.
We are living through a period of transformation, and I am eager to know where we are heading.
